The article discusses the need for tax reform in the United States. It references the Tax Reform Act of 1986, signed into law by former President Ronald Reagan, which simplified the tax code and led to economic growth. However, since then, the tax code has become complex and burdensome, making the US one of the highest taxed nations in the developed world. The article argues that tax reform is necessary to revive the economy and empower the middle class. It states that the proposed tax reform plan will make the tax code simple, fair, and easy to understand, and will cut taxes for hardworking, middle-class families. The article concludes by calling for the rekindling of America's middle-class miracle.